Network ACL (NACL)

What is NACL?

Network ACL (Network Access Control List) is a subnet-level firewall that controls inbound and outbound traffic for an entire subnet.

Simple Definition

NACL protects the entire subnet by allowing or denying network traffic.

Real-Life Example

Imagine an apartment.

Apartment Gate → NACL
Individual House Door → Security Group

The gate decides who can enter the apartment, while the house door decides who can enter the house.

Features
Works at the Subnet Level.
Controls both Inbound and Outbound traffic.
Supports Allow and Deny rules.
Rules are processed in ascending order (Rule Number).
It is Stateless.
What is Stateless?

If you allow inbound traffic, you must also allow outbound traffic.

Example:

Inbound  : Allow Port 22
Outbound : Allow Port 22

Both rules are required.

Interview Question
What is the difference between Security Group and NACL?
Security Group	NACL
Instance Level	Subnet Level
Stateful	Stateless
Only Allow Rules	Allow & Deny Rules
Easy Way to Remember

NACL = Subnet Firewall
