NIC (Network Interface Card)

What is NIC?

A NIC (Network Interface Card) is a hardware or virtual network adapter that allows a computer or server to communicate with a network.

Simple Definition

NIC is a device that connects a computer or server to a network.

Real-Life Example

Think of your laptop.

Without a Wi-Fi card or Ethernet card, it cannot connect to the internet.

That Wi-Fi/Ethernet card is called a NIC.

Similarly,

Laptop → Physical NIC
AWS EC2 → Virtual NIC (ENI)
Why Do We Use NIC?
Connects a server to the network.
Sends and receives network traffic.
Provides a MAC Address.
Enables communication with other devices.
In AWS

AWS does not use the term NIC directly.

Instead, AWS provides ENI (Elastic Network Interface), which is a virtual NIC.

An ENI contains:

Private IP Address
Public/Elastic IP (Optional)
MAC Address
Security Groups
Interview Question
What is NIC?

A Network Interface Card (NIC) is a hardware or virtual network adapter that enables a computer or server to communicate over a network.

Difference Between NIC and ENI
NIC	ENI
General networking term	AWS-specific term
Physical or Virtual	Virtual only
Used in Computers & Servers	Used in AWS EC2
Connects to a Network	Connects EC2 to a VPC
